<p>Secondly I have almost always been in similar situations like this, where I go from enthusiasm at the beginning then slowly losing interest until I end up in a half done projects which I completely forgot why I even started it. So this time I want to see things through, I want to know what would happen in the end (if there‚Äôs an end to this ) I think had my fair share of (what-if)s so far. Finishing things really improve our mental state since it leaves little to overthink about.</p>

<h2 id="the-least-comfortable-choice">the least comfortable choice.</h2>
<p>It‚Äôs easy to come up with excuses to give up. The way I thought about this is actually me just being both lazy and coward if you think your content is not good enough you improve it, do not giving up the whole thing. 
I really hope that I‚Äôll be able to do as many uncomfortable things in my life as possible. Almost all of the good things (and people ) require certain level of risk and discomfort at first.</p>
<h2 id="when-will-i-ever-stop">When will I ever stop?</h2>
<p>Now that I made things clear on why I would keep blogging it‚Äôs time to tell you when will I stop. Actually there‚Äôs is basically one thing I‚Äôm  afraid of becoming which is being fraud. I don‚Äôt like pretentious things or people.
There‚Äôs a song called ‚Äúsmoke and mirror‚Äù by gotye I always feel nervous when listen to it, Because I‚Äôm afraid of getting used to people praising my mediocre skills. and no I‚Äôm not hating on myself here or trying to be humble, but I think that‚Äôs they don‚Äôt know enough about the things I do to make a good judgment. For example if someone who doesn‚Äôt even know what a  web server is kept telling you that you‚Äôre a good back-end developer it wouldn‚Äôt mean anything to you right ? .</p>

